english:
  title: A Prayer for Rain to the Heavenly Worthy of Thunder and Lightning Manifestation at the Sogyeong Bureau
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Great Way is the source of all existence—who can fathom its mysterious workings? When utmost sincerity moves the gaze of the Three Pure Ones, we receive the hidden blessing. Thus do I, with humble heart, reverently present this modest ritual of purification.

    I reflect upon my unworthiness in inheriting the great legacy, upon the burden of this precarious position—both infinitely blessed and infinitely fraught with care. Heaven alone is to be feared, and it responds to truth, not empty ceremony. Yet my failings and oversights are manifold, and calamities have descended thick upon us.

    Spring brought no rain; summer too withholds its moisture. I dread the barley will not ripen properly. The fields have lost their season of turning, and the weeding cannot be done at the proper time. How then can the harvest flourish? Though my longing for clouds reaches ever skyward, my sincerity has not yet moved Heaven. Brief showers threaten, then scatter. The sun breaks through, bright and harsh. Clouds gather only to disperse again, scattered by the wind. The drought demon rages like consuming fire, and the crops lie withered.

    Agriculture is the foundation of the state—when a single grain fails to ripen, famine follows. Rice is the heaven of the people—three days without food, and life extinguishes. Now that spring's planting season has been lost, how can we hope for autumn's harvest? Though this calamity stems from human error, does it not also diminish Heaven's virtue of nurturing all things? Surely I alone deserve the harshest punishment, yet must the ten thousand people suffer the anguish of want?

    My heart surges with emotion; my will rises to the Celestial Lord. Though Heaven stands high and the stars shine distant, seeming beyond knowing, when clouds gather and rain descends, it is through borrowed power of divine aid. Therefore do we now enact the sacred rites prescribed in the Golden Registry, solemnly conducting the ceremonies in this sanctified hall.

    Humbly I pray: Turn swiftly the celestial chariot; manifest resplendent the divine radiance. Let clouds drape the sky in generous abundance, let the moon move with torrential downpour. Grant us rain and sunshine, warmth and cold, wind—all five in perfect measure. Let seeds take root and sprout, grow firm and fair, fill their grain with substance, and bring the hundred crops to ripeness.
  footnotes:
    - 'The Three Pure Ones (三淸) represent the highest deities in Daoism: the Primordial Celestial Worthy, the Heavenly Worthy of the Numinous Treasure, and the Heavenly Worthy of the Way and Virtue.'
    - The ritual described follows Daoist practices for celestial petition, where sincere devotion is believed to move divine intervention.
